Billboard Top 100 Data Exploration

Matthew Ruyter

Introduction:¶

It probably comes as no suprise to most that music has undergone a lot of change over the years. Genres of music come and go, and different cultural shifts express themselves in the form of new music year after year. The goal of this project is to identify and analyze the trends of change over the past 50 years, if they exist. The analysis will focus on 50 years of Billboard top 100 tracks, from 1971 to 2020. To develop an idea of the types of song characteristics that we may be looking for, let's observe an example. Take a Billboard top 100 song from 1971 and 2020 which share the same genre, "soft rock". The songs are 'Joy to the World' by Three Dog Night and 'Circles' by Post Malone.

An excerpt of the main verse from Joy to the World looks like:

Singin' joy to the world
All the boys and girls now
Joy to the fishes in the deep blue sea
Joy to you and me

An excerpt from the main verse of Circles looks like:

I dare you to do something
I'm waiting on you again
So I don't take the blame
Run away, but we're running in circles
Run away, run away, run away

These songs are both within the top 2 songs in their respective years on the Billboard Top 100 charts. An interesting and somewhat obvious observation that can be made is that they take on very different moods. It would appear that Circles from 2020 is defintely more sad than the aformentioned, just by looking at the main verse. This project will look much more closely at this trend, to discern if there is a significant decline or increase in musical characteristics from 1971 to 2020.

Hypothesis:¶

$H_{0}:$ music has no discernable pattern of change over the past 50 years of Billboard Top 100s.

$H_{1}:$ music does have discernable patterns of change over the past 50 years of Billboard Top 100s.

Data Collection:¶

In order to infer music characteristics for Billboard Top 100 songs, we need a way of retreiving the Billboard Top 100 songs over the 50 year period. To do this, we will use the Spotify API along with a precompiled list of of 50 playlists made by various Spotify users.

First, we establish the connection with the API, using our account's client_id and client_secret keys. These keys will be stored in the file named "Spotify_credentials.txt" in order to not reveal the connection keys openly to the public. The connection will be made by using the python API wrapper named Spotipy. It will allow for a relatively seamless connection process and give us access to some very useful functions. An OAuth protocol is used to establish the connection with our credentials.

Connecting to the Spotify API:¶

In [6]:
import spotipy
from spotipy.oauth2 import SpotifyClientCredentials

with open('Spotify_credentials.txt') as f:
    keys = f.readlines()
    f.close()

# client id:
client_id = keys[0].strip()

# client secret:
client_secret = keys[1].strip()

# initialize spotipy, the Spotify API wrapper: 
client_credentials_manager = SpotifyClientCredentials(client_id=client_id, client_secret=client_secret)
sp = spotipy.Spotify(client_credentials_manager=client_credentials_manager)

Advantages of the Spotify API:¶

The Spotify API allows for a lot of cool and useful features to be leveraged. The two that will be particulalry useful is the ability to look up playlists and songs by their unique 22 character alphanumeric ID's, and the ability to look up song audio details by using the audio_features function. The audio_features function returns the following information:

  • Instrumentalness: This value represents the amount of vocals in the song. The closer it is to 1.0, the more instrumental the song is.
  • Acousticness: This value describes how acoustic a song is. A score of 1.0 means the song is most likely to be an acoustic one.
  • Liveness: This value describes the probability that the song was recorded with a live audience. According to the official documentation “a value above 0.8 provides strong likelihood that the track is live”.
  • Speechiness: “Speechiness detects the presence of spoken words in a track”. If the speechiness of a song is above 0.66, it is probably made of spoken words, a score between 0.33 and 0.66 is a song that may contain both music and words, and a score below 0.33 means the song does not have any speech.
  • Energy: “(energy) represents a perceptual measure of intensity and activity. Typically, energetic tracks feel fast, loud, and noisy”.
  • Danceability: “Danceability describes how suitable a track is for dancing based on a combination of musical elements including tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity. A value of 0.0 is least danceable and 1.0 is most danceable”.
  • Valence: “A measure from 0.0 to 1.0 describing the musical positiveness conveyed by a track. Tracks with high valence sound more positive (e.g. happy, cheerful, euphoric), while tracks with low valence sound more negative (e.g. sad, depressed, angry)”.
  • Key: A number describing the main group of notes that make up the track.
  • Loudness: A value ranging between -60 and 0 dB, describing the loudness of a given track.
  • Tempo: The overall estimated tempo of a track in beats per minute (BPM).

While all of these features for each individual song will be compiled into a large dataframe, not all of them will be particulary useful, as we will see.

Getting the Billboard Top 100 song data:¶

The data will be gathered using user created playlists for each of the Billboard Top 100s since 1970. The playlist IDs are unique 22 digit strings of letters an numbers that the Spotify API uses to uniquely identify a playlist. We will iterate through the IDs in the "Top_100_IDs.txt" file and gather the associated information about the songs within.

Make an array of all needed playlist IDs, these are in sorted order from 1970 to 2020:¶

In [7]:
ids = []
with open('Top_100_IDs.txt') as f:
    ids = f.readlines()
    f.close()

for i in range(len(ids)): 
    ids[i] = ids[i].strip()

Now that we have all of the IDs for each playlist, we can get the respective song information. The information that we are interested in is each individual track ID, name and artist. We get this information by simply iterating over the year interval and using the playlist_tracks function from the API. The track responses are indexable as seen below. These will all be compiled into a dataframe.

In [10]:
i = 0
frames = []
for y in range(1970, 2021):
    tracks = sp.playlist_tracks(ids[i])
    
    to_frame = []

    for track in tracks['items']:
        
        #ID
        track_id = (track["track"]["uri"]).split(':')[2]
    
        #Track name
        track_name = track["track"]["name"]
    
        #Main Artist
        artist_name = track["track"]["artists"][0]["name"]
        
        # make the list to be turned into a dataframe
        track_info = [y, track_name, track_id, artist_name]
        to_frame.append(track_info)

    arry = np.array(to_frame)
    df = pd.DataFrame(arry, columns=['year','track','track_ID','artist_name'])
    frames.append(df)
    i+=1

Let's look at our data:¶

Now that the data has been gathered, let's take a look at it. We are specicifically looking for trends over the 50 year period. First we will create a dataframe of averages for each audio characteristic and year, respectively.

Some initial key observations from the above graphs follow:

  • There is a steady decline in valence throughout the last 50 years. This means that the overall positivity conveyed by top tracks has decreased over the timeframe.
  • The average energy of songs also appears to be on the rise, with a sharp decrease occuring around 2010, up to the year 2020.

This is in support of the alternative hypothesis, which states that there has been a change in the type of music that is most popular over the 50 years.

In order to identify a clear change in popular music over the past 50 years, let's define a new metric. The metric will be attitude, and it will depend on energy and valence. The attitude classes will be as follows:

  • Agressive: classifies songs with lower than average valence and higher than average enregy.
  • Happy: classifies songs with higher that average valence and higher than average energy.
  • Sad: classifies songs with lower then average valence and lower than average energy.
  • Calm: classifies songs with higher than average valence and lower than average valence.

Generating a new metric: Attitude¶

In order to analyze the attitude of the Billboard tracks over the past 50 years, we will take random samples of the data. The data will be sampled by taking a random subset of 25 tracks from each year. In total, we will plot the attitude of 1,250 tracks. The data will be categorized into two 25 year intervals. Ideally, we will be able to see clusters of songs from the 2 intervals in different quadrants of the scatter plot. This will allow us to conclude that the attitude of music has changed over time.

One tailed Z-test:¶

We will use the stats and stests modules in order to conduct a one tailed z test on the above data. This will allow us to compare the difference of each interval's mean valence to the overall mean valence. Our test will conclude whether our samples of music from 1971-1995 and 1996-2020 differ significantly with respect to average valence, when compared to the mean valence of the entire 50 years.

The average valence of of the entire dataset is given as:

In [20]:
print(complete_data['valence'].mean())

In [21]:
from statsmodels.stats import weightstats as stests

interval1 = all_samples.loc[all_samples['category'] == '1971-1995']
interval2 = all_samples.loc[all_samples['category'] == '1996-2020']

# first test, on interval 1
ztest1 ,pval1 = stests.ztest(interval1['valence'], x2=None, value=0.58956)

# second test, on interval 2 
ztest2 ,pval2 = stests.ztest(interval2['valence'], x2=None, value=0.58956)

# make the display nice
d = {'interval': ['1971-1995','1996-2020'], 
     'pval': [pval1, pval2],
     'reject Ho at alpha 0.25':['yes','yes'], 
     'mean': [interval1['valence'].mean(), interval2['valence'].mean()]}
test = pd.DataFrame(data = d)

display(test)
interval pval reject Ho at alpha 0.25 mean
0 1971-1995 6.909650e-10 yes 0.648392
1 1996-2020 1.310029e-07 yes 0.544355

In each test, we can very well conclude that the mean valence of our samples differs significantly from the mean of the entire dataset. We reject the null hypothesis. Additionally, we can clearly see the observed results from the graph. The mean valence of the earlier interval was higher by approximately .10. This describes explicitly the shift of music from 'calm' and 'happy' to 'sad' and 'agressive' over the last 50 years of Billboard Top 100s.

Analyzing uniqueness:¶

In the plots above, we see that 'speechiness', Spotify's metric for number of spoken words in a song, is increasing on average. What is interesting about this data is that while acousticness and instrumentalness are decreasing, danceability and speechiness appear to be increasing. This could be due to the nature of the instruments used to create popular music in more recent times. As more technology is used to create melodies, the instrumental and acoustic values of songs go down. However danceability, based on tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity of the song, goes up. With all of these factors at play, we still observe an increased number of spoken words in song on average, as indicated by the speechiness values of the tracks.

Observation:¶

to get a better understanding of the speechiness of the selected tracks, we will compare uniqueness of words over 10 year intervals. Since speechiness is increasing over the 50 years, the expected result is that newer music will have a higher uniqueness value than older music.

Connecting to the Genius Lyrics API:¶

We will be using the Genius Lyrics API in order to collect the lyric data for the Billboard Top 100 songs. Similarly to the above Spotify API connection, we will streamline the process by utilizing a nice wrapper for teh Genius API, called lyricsgenius.

Here we extablish a connection to the API, using the user credentials stored in the local directory titled "genius_tokens.txt".

In [22]:
# import the lyricsgenius API
import lyricsgenius

# create a connection to the Genius API
with open('genius_token.txt') as f:
    token = f.readlines()[0]
f.close()
gen = lyricsgenius.Genius(token)

Now we can utilize the API's functionality to retrieve the lyrics of every single song in our 50 year interval. The lyrics are found by iterating all of the songs. For each song, we search the song using it's name and the search_song function. If we get a result from the search, we then get the lyrics by the song.lyrics operation. The lyrics that are scraped contain breaks, brackets, and various song element descriptors that we would like to parse out. They will be parsed during the iteration of all of the songs, using the regex import.

Note: Due to the excessive time (2 hours) it takes to retrieve all of the lyrics, this was only executed a single time and then the data was exported to a csv stored in the local directory for ease of data usage in the future.

Cleaning the lyrics further:¶

We will separate contractions as to not confuse single letters with words when anlayzing lyrics. Also, we will remove certain words that have no contextual meaning but will surely occur often, such as 'and', 'of', 'or',...etc. In order to parse out these words, we will use the spaCy and contractions libraries.

SpaCy will allow us to introduce a precompiled dictionary of 'stopwords'. Stopwords are the words described above, and comparing the lyrics here to the dictionary will allow us to get rid of them.

the contractions library will allow us to remove contrains by way of the fix() function on each indidual lyric. This library contains precompiled contractions which it matches these lyrics to. Once it matches, it replaces that contraction with the expanded form. ie: 'would've' becomes 'would have'.

In [26]:
# import contractions and spaCy
import contractions
import spacy

# Used remove words that hold no semantic meaning: 'stopwords'
stopwords = (spacy.load('en_core_web_sm')).Defaults.stop_words

#copy lyric data for next part: 
less_clean_lyrics = lyric_data

for i,row in lyric_data.iterrows():
    expanded = []
    lyrics1 = row['lyrics']
    
    # remove contractions:
    for lyric in lyrics1.split():
        expanded.append(contractions.fix(lyric))
    lyrics2 = ' '.join(expanded)
    
    # remove stop words:
    no_stops = [lyric for lyric in lyrics2.split() if lyric not in stopwords]
    lyrics3 = ' '.join(no_stops)
    
    # replace in the dataframe:
    lyric_data.loc[i,'lyrics'] = lyrics3

Now that the lyrics are clean, we can use them in our analysis of lyric uniqueness. This uniqueness value for each year interval will be calculated as $ratio_{unique}$. A value closer to 1 indicates a large number of unique lyrics.

$ratio_{unique} = \frac{lyric_{unique}}{lyric_{total}}$. here, $lyric_{unique}$ is the number of unique lyrics, and $lyric_{total}$ is the total number of lyrics.

The count_unique function simply accumulates lyrics and as it iterates further, it checks against the accumulator, and adds if the current lyric is not already in the accumulator.

In [27]:
def count_unique(sub_str):
    acc = []
    for i in range(0,len(sub_str)):
        if sub_str[i] not in acc: 
            acc.append(sub_str[i])
    return len(acc)

ratios = []
for i in range(1971,2021):
    sub_str = ' '
    sub_df = lyric_data.loc[lyric_data['year'] == i]
    for j,row in sub_df.iterrows():
        sub_str += row['lyrics']
        
    # get the length of the lyric text for year i:
    num_lyrics = len(sub_str.split())
    
    # count the unique lyrics for year i:
    num_unique = count_unique(sub_str.split())
    
    # calculate the ratio
    ratio = num_unique/num_lyrics
    
    # make the list
    ratios.append([i,ratio])
    
ratio_df1 = pd.DataFrame(ratios, columns = ['year','ratio'])

Look at the uniqueness ratios:¶

Let's put together a bar plot to look at the uniqueness ratios over the years.

In [28]:
# make a bar plot
plt.figure(figsize = (11,4))
ax = sns.barplot(x = ratio_df1['year'], y = ratio_df1['ratio'])
adj = plt.xticks(rotation = 90)
plt.title('Lyrical Uniqueness of Top 100 music from 1971 to 2020')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Ratio')
plt.show()

Interestingly, the plot above does not show a very clear linear increase in lyric uniqueness that we expected. This result was expected due to the speechiness values of songs increasing over time. The fact that we did not observe the expected result indicates that even though newer music is more wordy, it actually doesn't contain a significantly larger proportion of unique lyrics. In fact, the highest spikes in this ratio are in the 80's and the late 90s.

Observation:¶

Is one interval, such as 1971-1995, more word-wise unique than the 1996-2020 interval? Word uniqueness seems to not have linearly increased or decreased over time, which is interesting because speachiness has increased over time. One would think that the period with more speaking would contain more unique words, or at least have a higher probability of containing more unique words.

Let's find out which period really is more unique:¶

We'll compare the 1971-1995 period to 1996-2020 by way of 2 more one tailed z tests, as done above. The reason we use a z test is because we wish to compare our independent sampled ratio means to the ratio mean of the complete dataset. The mean ratio over all time is given by:

In [29]:
print(ratio_df1['ratio'].mean())

0.2693644228512843
In [30]:
# ready the frame
ratio_df1['category'] = 0
for i,row in ratio_df1.iterrows():
    if row['year'] in range(1971,1996):
        ratio_df1.loc[i, 'category'] = '1971-1995'
    elif row['year'] in range(1996,2021):
        ratio_df1.loc[i, 'category'] = '1996-2020'

interval1 = ratio_df1.loc[ratio_df1['category'] == '1971-1995']
interval2 = ratio_df1.loc[ratio_df1['category'] == '1996-2020']

# first test, on interval 1
ztest1 ,pval1 = stests.ztest(interval1['ratio'], x2=None, value=0.26936)

# second test, on interval 2 
ztest2 ,pval2 = stests.ztest(interval2['ratio'], x2=None, value=0.26936)

# make the display nice
d = {'interval': ['1971-1995','1996-2020'], 
     'pval': [pval1,pval2],
     'reject Ho at 0.25': ['no', 'no'],
     'mean ratio': [interval1['ratio'].mean(), interval2['ratio'].mean()]}
test = pd.DataFrame(data = d)
display(test)
interval pval reject Ho at 0.25 mean ratio
0 1971-1995 0.618106 no 0.263823
1 1996-2020 0.496597 no 0.274905

We cannot reject the null hypothesis by a significant amount, so we cannot conclude that the uniqueness of words is significantly different between the 2 time periods.

Conclusion:¶

We were able to gather some interesting points of data from our analysis. The key point being that yes, in fact, Billboard Top 100 music has experienced quite a few changes over the past 50 years. We reject the null hypothesis that things have remained largely the same. The nature of this change seem to be that music is shifting into a more negative direction and that there are more words used in popular music today, but the overall respective vocabulary ranges have remained largely the same.
